Yes — here is the **final start-to-end idea** you should use as your main pipeline.

Your final system is a **hybrid semantic change detection pipeline** for bi-temporal satellite images that first fixes geometry with geospatial and feature-based alignment, then performs class-aware semantic change detection for **water, building, road, and vegetation** using a SemDINO-style model, while using Self-Pair only to expand training data. This is the cleanest and most practical design because SemDINO is built for cross-temporal semantic alignment and multi-output prediction, while FLANN-based matching and homography are well suited for cheap global preregistration. [arxiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.09772)

## Final goal

Input:
- Two satellite images of the same area at time \(T1\) and time \(T2\).
- Images may have different tilt, season, illumination, or small geometric mismatch.

Output:
- Semantic map at \(T1\).
- Semantic map at \(T2\).
- Change masks for:
  - Water
  - Building
  - Road
  - Vegetation
- Optional transition map, such as vegetation \(\rightarrow\) building. Semantic change detection is explicitly about identifying both change location and semantic categories before and after transition, which is exactly what SemDINO targets. [emergentmind](https://www.emergentmind.com/papers/2606.09772)

## Full pipeline

### 1. Data preparation

First, collect bi-temporal image pairs and bring them into a common geospatial frame.

- Reproject both images to the same CRS.
- Resample to the same spatial resolution.
- Clip to the same geographic extent.
- Normalize radiometry consistently across both times.

This step reduces false change caused by coordinate mismatch rather than real land-cover change. Semantic change detection methods are known to be sensitive to pseudo-changes from registration and appearance variation, so this stage is essential. [arxiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.09772)

### 2. Geometric preprocessing

Use a **classical global alignment block** before deep learning.

#### 2.1 Feature extraction and matching
- Try **SIFT** first if texture quality is decent.
- Use **ORB** if you need faster and lighter matching.
- Match descriptors with **FLANN**.
- Filter matches using **Lowe’s ratio test**. OpenCV documents this ratio filtering as a way to reject ambiguous matches. [docs.opencv](https://docs.opencv.org/4.x/d1/de0/tutorial_py_feature_homography.html)

#### 2.2 Robust transform estimation
- Use matched keypoints to estimate **homography** with `cv.findHomography(..., RANSAC)`.
- Warp one image to the reference geometry of the other.
- Keep only inlier-supported transformations.

OpenCV notes that homography estimation requires enough correct matches and that RANSAC separates inliers from outliers, which is why this is the right lightweight global registration step. [blog.finxter](https://blog.finxter.com/5-effective-ways-to-implement-flann-based-feature-matching-in-opencv-python/)

#### 2.3 Fallback condition
If SIFT/ORB + FLANN gives too few inliers or unstable homography:
- Switch to a stronger matcher such as **LoFTR or LightGlue**.
- Do not force bad homography when the matching quality is poor.

So your registration rule is:
- **Default** = SIFT/ORB + FLANN + RANSAC homography.
- **Fallback** = deep matcher only when needed.

### 3. Remove optical flow from the main design

Do **not** keep optical flow as a standard stage in the final pipeline.

Why:
- In high-resolution satellite imagery, buildings can appear leaned or shifted due to off-nadir viewing.
- Dense local warping can distort building structure and create false building change.
- Your semantic model should handle remaining small local offsets better than aggressive optical-flow correction.

So the final architecture is **simpler and safer** if you remove optical flow from the default chain.

### 4. Main model

Use a **SemDINO-style semantic change detector** as the central model.

SemDINO is designed around:
- Dual-branch encoding for two times.
- Fusion of CNN features and frozen DINOv3 features.
- Multi-scale temporal interaction.
- Semantic purification and change enhancement.
- Joint prediction of binary change mask and bi-temporal semantic maps. [arxiv](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2606.09772.pdf)

That is why it fits your case much better than a pure binary change detector.

#### 4.1 Backbone strategy for limited compute
Since you do not have H100 access:
- Use **frozen or partially frozen DINOv3** features.
- Train only a lightweight decoder / fusion / prediction head.
- Optionally combine DINOv3 with a light CNN backbone for multi-scale detail.

This preserves semantic strength while keeping compute manageable, which is consistent with the SemDINO design idea of combining frozen DINOv3 with task-specific modules. [arxiv](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2606.09772.pdf)

### 5. Training data strategy

Use **Self-Pair** only for augmentation, not as the main detector.

Self-Pair is meant to synthesize changed image pairs from single-source remote sensing images so you can expand supervision without needing many expensive real bi-temporal labels. The official repository also positions it as a change synthesis approach for object change detection in remote sensing imagery. [openaccess.thecvf](https://openaccess.thecvf.com/content/WACV2023/papers/Seo_Self-Pair_Synthesizing_Changes_From_Single_Source_for_Object_Change_Detection_WACV_2023_paper.pdf)

#### 5.1 How you use Self-Pair
- Start with your real aligned bi-temporal pairs.
- Add Self-Pair-generated synthetic pairs from single-time labeled images.
- Mix real and synthetic data during training.

#### 5.2 Why this helps
- Improves diversity of object transitions.
- Reduces overfitting to limited real pairs.
- Helps the model learn semantic changes instead of only intensity differences. [github](https://github.com/seominseok0429/Self-Pair-for-Change-Detection)

### 6. Prediction targets

Do not train only a single “changed / unchanged” mask.

Train for:
- Semantic segmentation at \(T1\).
- Semantic segmentation at \(T2\).
- Binary change mask.
- Derived per-class change masks.
- Optional transition matrix or transition map.

This is better than just “building changed,” because it lets you infer:
- vegetation \(\rightarrow\) building
- water \(\rightarrow\) road
- road \(\rightarrow\) vegetation

That makes the pipeline more useful and more stable for debugging and analysis. SemDINO explicitly includes bi-temporal semantic maps and binary change prediction in a unified framework. [emergentmind](https://www.emergentmind.com/papers/2606.09772)

## Training formulation

Use a multi-task loss:

\[
L = \lambda_1 L_{\text{seg}}^{T1} + \lambda_2 L_{\text{seg}}^{T2} + \lambda_3 L_{\text{change}} + \lambda_4 L_{\text{edge}}
\]

SemDINO includes multi-branch prediction and edge-related constraints in its unified design, so a multi-task formulation is aligned with the paper’s overall structure. [arxiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.09772)

Practical choices:
- Cross-entropy or focal loss for segmentation.
- BCE or focal loss for change mask.
- Class weights for underrepresented classes like road or water.
- Dice-style auxiliary term if your masks are sparse.

## Inference strategy

Because satellite images are large, use **sliding-window inference**.

- Crop into overlapping tiles.
- Use 25–50% overlap.
- Blend predictions smoothly across overlaps.
- Reconstruct the full-scene output.

Do **not** use non-overlapping tiling, because it creates boundary artifacts and misses changes at patch edges.

## Final deployment workflow

Here is the final start-to-end system you should follow:

1. Collect bi-temporal satellite image pairs.
2. Reproject, resample, and clip both images to the same grid.
3. Run SIFT or ORB feature extraction.
4. Match with FLANN.
5. Apply Lowe ratio filtering. [docs.opencv](https://docs.opencv.org/4.x/d5/d6f/tutorial_feature_flann_matcher.html)
6. Estimate homography with RANSAC. [docs.opencv](https://docs.opencv.org/4.x/d1/de0/tutorial_py_feature_homography.html)
7. Warp one image to the other.
8. If alignment fails, switch to LoFTR or LightGlue fallback.
9. Build training data using:
   - Real aligned pairs
   - Self-Pair synthetic pairs [openaccess.thecvf](https://openaccess.thecvf.com/content/WACV2023/papers/Seo_Self-Pair_Synthesizing_Changes_From_Single_Source_for_Object_Change_Detection_WACV_2023_paper.pdf)
10. Train a SemDINO-style semantic change detector with frozen or partially frozen DINOv3 features. [emergentmind](https://www.emergentmind.com/papers/2606.09772)
11. Predict:
   - semantic \(T1\)
   - semantic \(T2\)
   - binary change
   - class-wise change masks
12. Run overlapping tiled inference on full images.
13. Post-process masks with small-component removal or morphological cleanup if needed.
14. Produce final outputs for water, building, road, and vegetation change.

## Final one-line thesis

Your final idea is:

**A hybrid bi-temporal satellite semantic change detection pipeline that performs georeferencing correction, feature-based global co-registration with FLANN and RANSAC homography, fallback deep matching when needed, SemDINO-style semantic change detection with frozen DINOv3 features, and Self-Pair-based synthetic augmentation to predict water, building, road, and vegetation changes across time.** [docs.opencv](https://docs.opencv.org/4.x/d5/d6f/tutorial_feature_flann_matcher.html)

